<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-457-578  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 457 578.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 22 1990 v7 n20 pS22(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Graphical interface switches the focus for DOS diehards. (PC WeekSpecial Report: Windows 3.0)(Windows 3.0 will impact MS-DOS usagepattern)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lovejoy, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (product development).andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceComputer GraphicsCompetitionMS-DOSUser-FriendlinessUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>With its emphasis on pictures and menus instead of words and commands, thegraphical user interface of Windows 3.0 may change the computing culture ofthe DOS-based world.andM;&quot;People's expectations will be very different about what they're going toneed to learn about computing,&quot; said Tandy Trower, director of user-interfacearchitecture at Microsoft Corp. in Redmond, Wash.andP;  &quot;A lot of people are slowcoming into computing, primarily because it seems too hard to remember allthe commands.&quot;andM;With Windows screens, however, users don't need to remember what theiroptions are or the syntax of issuing commands.andM;The range of choices is presented on screen, and the user needs only toselect the desired option with the double-click of a mouse.andM;&quot;The evolution we're looking at is what attracts people -- they don't have toremember as much,&quot; said Trower.andM;The goal of a Windows type of graphical user interface is for users to dotheir work without consciously being aware that they're interacting with acomputer.andM;&quot;This allows you to focus more on the task, when there are fewer distractionsthat affect you while you're doing your task,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;People always talk about cars as being a consistent interface -- thesteering wheel and the gas pedal are always in the same place,&quot; he said.andO;&quot;But if you're in a rental car in the dark, and you strap yourself in andfumble around trying to find the lights, you have to go through some mentalorientation.andP;  Meanwhile, what you really want to do is find out how to getout of the parking lot.andM;&quot;What Windows provides is a better way for new users to come into thecomputer environment,&quot; Trower continued.andP;  &quot;It lets you make the transitionfrom DOS to the graphical environment.andP;  It lets you get the best of bothworlds.&quot;andM;The Human FactorandM;Much of the Windows 3.0 user interface was designed around human factors: howpeople learn and remember as well as what is aesthetically pleasing.andM;The staff of Microsoft's user-interface group includes cognitivepsychologists who specialize in perception and learning.andM;Trower explained why some people perceive a graphical interface as easier towork with than a command-driven interface: &quot;The key is the difference betweenrecall and recognition.andP;  People are lousy at recall, but they're very good atrecognition.andP;  I can recognize a person's face, but for some reason their nameescapes me.andM;&quot;It's the same thing for your environment,&quot; he went on.andP;  &quot;If you don't usethese commands every day, they tend to fade out of memory.andP;  It's easier tosee and point and do than it is to learn and remember.&quot; -- P.L.andO;</TEXT></DOC>